\int_0^\pi \ln\cos x~dx
u = x - \pi/2
\ln\cos x = \ln\sin u
J = \displaystyle \int_0^{\pi/2} \ln\sin u~du = -\dfrac{\pi\cdot \ln2}{2}
I = -\pi\cdot \ln2
I = \int_{0}^\pi \ln\cos x~dx = -\dfrac{\pi\cdot \ln2}{2} + \int_{\pi/2}^{\pi} \ln\cos x~dx = -\frac{\pi\cdot \ln 2}{2} + J
